I really wasn't feeling the connection with myself today and was struggling getting into the session, my mind was on everything else and my breathing was out of sync, I got tired after doing the poses for a few seconds and I just wanted to quit it and go lie in my bed. My thoughts were a mess, until we were doing the tree pose and Adriene talked about how it's a beautiful part of the proces to fall, to get out of the habit of wanting to nail it and to be curious of the falling. I could instantly feel my mind and my breathing calm and I was able to fully enjoy the last few minutes with no disturbances.¬†

Personally, it was eye opening being told that we don't have to fear falling or not getting it completely right. Failing isn't something to be feared but a part of the proces in everything we do, it's how we learn and we can feel curious about this instead of fearing it. It's crazy how applicable these words are for so many aspects of our lives outside of yoga. There's something in my life I've put off doing for a long time now, but I want to be able to explore it with curiosity instead going forward. This was such a nice realisation along with the session, thank you for today.

In addition to this challenge, I am walking with a friend during a 14 day meditation challenge in another app.  Today's practice in that space was all about inviting others along for the journey to support us, no matter if they are in our physical space or not.  I couldn't help but think of this community.  How beautiful is it that there are thousands of people actively seeking to heal, to love, to make space?  How powerful is it that we are working together in this way?  It's so easy to look at the world and see all the division, all the fear.  So easy to look at our neighbors and our partners and see them for what they don't provide us, what they can't be.  But if we let go of that fear for a bit, if we get curious about each other and let each other in, magic happens.

Grateful for all of you.  By doing this practice, not only are you serving yourselves, but everyone else you come in contact with.  Keep showing up.

Curiosity is the perfect name for today's practice. I've learned that whenever I can't nail a pose, it's usually because I'm not approaching it correctly. Heels not touching the ground in downward dog? It's because I was focused on pushing my heels down, rather than lifting my hips up. Don't just keep doing things the same way, because that's how you've always done them. Sometimes even a small change in your behavior can have drastic and long lasting results. Change requires curiosity.  So if you find yourself struggling with a pose today, take a step back and try approaching it differently. You might be surprised what you learn about your body in the process.
Accepting that falling is okay is something I still have to remind myself and this practice strengthened that reminder. üíï

T/W for mental health/self sabotage discussion, just in case.




I am really struggling with my mental health right now. But I wanted to take this opportunity to engage with yoga, since it does interest me, but I have a habit of now exploring the things that interest me, I don't let it grow because of some kind of fear. I've been doing this my whole life, which is very painful to face. And even doing yoga right now is difficult, since my brain is panicking a little bit, but today during the treepose I closed my eyes and fell and it felt right. If anyone is also struggling, please know, that your experience is valid and that you're not alone. Please do ask for help if you need it. You are worth it <3 
Also to follow up on the theme of this video, I wanted to pose a question: have you noticed any changes in your life that you can trace to your yoga practice?
